---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'init';
const description =
  'Bootstrap a repo with the full context engineering scaffolding. The single most leveraged move in Groundwork. One command, one repo, one time.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    Bootstrap a repo with the full context engineering scaffolding. The single
    most leveraged move in this skill. Run it once per repo and every other
    command has the artifacts it expects.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    Most repos either have no context files at all or one bloated
    <code>CLAUDE.md</code> that says "use good judgment" and "follow our
    conventions". Both fail in the same way: the agent has to guess. It guesses
    wrong, you spend the day correcting it, and "AI is unreliable" becomes the
    team's narrative.
  </p>
  <p>
    <code>init</code> replaces guessing with detection. It reads your repo
    (package manifests, scripts, recent commits) and emits a complete starter
    set of context files: one canonical <code>AGENTS.md</code>, with
    <code>CLAUDE.md</code> as a symlink to it and a five-line pointer file
    for each non-Codex harness you target. No duplication. No placeholders.
    No "TODO: implement this".
  </p>
  <p>
    The point is not the files. The point is that every other command in this
    skill (<a href={url('commands/plan/')}><code>plan</code></a>,
    <a href={url('commands/adr/')}><code>adr</code></a>,
    <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a>,
    <a href={url('commands/onboard/')}><code>onboard</code></a>) assumes
    these files exist. <code>init</code> is the foundation under the
    foundation.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      The motivation comes from the
      <a href={url('foundation/contextops-lifecycle/')}>ContextOps lifecycle</a>
      (Build stage) and the
      <a href={url('foundation/five-layer-stack/')}>five-layer stack</a>
      (Project layer). The full argument lives in the
      <a href={url('blueprint/#contextops')}>2026 Blueprint</a>.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>A brand new repo with no context files yet.</li>
    <li>
      A small or medium repo where nobody has written a <code>CLAUDE.md</code>
      yet. If one already exists and is just stale, use
      <a href={url('commands/document/')}><code>document</code></a> instead.
      It preserves history.
    </li>
    <li>
      Standardising an org's context engineering across multiple repos.
      <code>init</code> is the baseline; per-repo tweaks happen after.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <p>Depending on which harnesses you target, some subset of:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>AGENTS.md</code>, the canonical hand-edited source (aim under ~80 lines)</li>
    <li><code>CLAUDE.md</code> → <code>AGENTS.md</code> (symlink by default; two-file fallback for Windows / <code>core.symlinks=false</code>)</li>
    <li><code>.cursor/rules/main.mdc</code> for Cursor (5-line pointer with <code>alwaysApply: true</code>)</li>
    <li><code>.github/copilot-instructions.md</code> for GitHub Copilot (5-line pointer)</li>
    <li><code>.windsurf/rules/main.md</code> for Windsurf (5-line pointer)</li>
    <li><code>docs/decisions/</code>: README, a starter ADR, and a negative-space stub</li>
    <li><code>.context/hooks/check-context.sh</code> — slim pre-commit hook (ADR coverage + ADR status + package-manager drift; no parity check)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <code>AGENTS.md</code> is self-sufficient. The per-harness pointer files
    are five lines each: they say "read <code>/AGENTS.md</code>" and inline
    three non-negotiables. They are hand-maintained — short and stable enough
    that hand maintenance is fine.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Detect.</strong> Reads package manifests, scripts,
      <code>README.md</code>, recent commits. Identifies stack, package
      manager, test commands. Surfaces a one-paragraph summary before asking
      anything.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Ask five questions, never more.</strong>
      <em>Which harnesses?</em> <em>Which verification commands?</em>
      <em>Which conventions?</em> <em>Three-tier boundaries (Always / Ask first / Never)?</em>
      <em>Symlink CLAUDE.md or keep two files?</em>
      Pre-selects detected answers; you adjust.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Write <code>AGENTS.md</code></strong> directly from your
      answers. Self-sufficient; aim under ~80 lines. Overflow goes to
      <code>docs/agents/&lt;area&gt;.md</code> (harness-agnostic), not back
      into the root file.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Wire up <code>CLAUDE.md</code> and the per-harness pointers.</strong>
      Symlink by default; two-file fallback when symlinks are unavailable.
      For each non-Codex harness, drop the same 5-line pointer file at its
      hardcoded path.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Set up ADRs and the pre-commit hook.</strong> Suggests the
      install command for husky / pre-commit / lefthook if none is present.
      Does not silently install.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Run verification.</strong> The commands you picked actually
      execute. Failures are surfaced, not hidden.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="The quality bar" tone="mute">
    <p>
      No placeholder text. <code>AGENTS.md</code> under ~80 lines. Per-harness
      pointer files exactly the five-line shape, no duplicated rules. If the
      repo already had partial context files, they are not overwritten; you
      get a diff and decide.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>What this command does <em>not</em> do</h2>
  <p>
    <code>init</code> deliberately stops at scaffolding. It does not author
    skills, set up MCP servers, scope rules per directory, or onboard a
    specific task. Those have their own commands
    (<a href={url('commands/mcp/')}><code>mcp</code></a>,
    <a href={url('commands/scope/')}><code>scope</code></a>,
    <a href={url('commands/onboard/')}><code>onboard</code></a>)
    so that <code>init</code> stays predictable.
  </p>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/contextops-lifecycle/')}>ContextOps lifecycle</a>.
      Where Build sits in the larger story.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/five-layer-stack/')}>The five-layer stack</a>.
      Why per-harness files belong in the Project layer and nothing else.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>Good practices</a>.
      Standardised initialisation, scoped rules, defensive commits.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/harness-reference/')}>Harness reference</a>.
      Where each harness expects files.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#contextops')}>2026 Blueprint: ContextOps</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="init" />
</Doc>
